\begin_inset VSpace medskip
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
A bit of a false taxonomy:
 Many tax avoidance schemes have never been tested in a court,
 and may well be illegal...
\begin_inset VSpace medskip
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Classical model is Allingham & Sandmo (JPubE 1972) extended by Yitzhaki (1974)
\begin_inset VSpace medskip
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Builds on Becker's (1968) theory of crime
\begin_inset VSpace medskip
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Takes true income as given,
 focus only on decision of what to report to the authorities
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator plain
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Frame
\begin_inset Argument 4
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Allingham & Sandmo (1972):
 Setup
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Consider individual with true income 
\begin_inset Formula $W$
\end_inset

 facing linear tax 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

 on reported income.
 
\begin_inset VSpace medskip
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The individual chooses to evade an amount 
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset


\begin_inset VSpace medskip
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
If they are not caught,
 their net income is
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
Y=W-t\left(W-E\right)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
If they are caught,
 they pay a penalty rate 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta>t$
\end_inset

 on the evaded amount and have net income
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
Z=\left(1-t\right)W-\left(\theta-t\right)E
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
They are audited with probability 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator plain
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Frame
\begin_inset Argument 4
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Allingham & Sandmo (1972):
 Solution
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Individual maximizes expected utility
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
V=\left(1-p\right)U\left(Y\right)+pU\left(Z\right)
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset VSpace medskip
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
FOCs yield
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{U^{\prime}\left(Z\right)}{U^{\prime}\left(Y\right)}=\frac{1-p}{p}\frac{t}{\theta-t}
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset VSpace medskip
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Comparative statics:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\frac{\partial E}{\partial\theta} & <0\\
\frac{\partial E}{\partial p} & <0
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator plain
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Frame
\begin_inset Argument 4
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Allingham & Sandmo (1972) - Yitzhaki (1974)
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Effect of tax rate in A-S model:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{\partial E}{\partial t}=\underbrace{-\frac{W-E}{1-t}\frac{\partial E}{\partial W}}_{\text{Income Effect}<0}+\underbrace{S}_{\text{Substitution Effect}>0}
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset VSpace medskip
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Substitution effect (consumption cheaper in unaudited state) seems unintuitive,
 drives ambiguous prediction.
 
\begin_inset VSpace medskip
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Yitzhaki (1974):
 This is because penalty is on evaded income not evaded tax.
 If instead penalty is 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta tE$
\end_inset

,
 then
\begin_inset VSpace medskip
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{U^{\prime}\left(Z\right)}{U^{\prime}\left(Y\right)}=\frac{1-p}{p\left(\theta-1\right)}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
No more substitution effect,
 only income effect
\end_layout

\end_deeper
